5 98. Ut with the subj. of the historical perfect is not found in the Dialogue or in Germania, but is common in the History and the An- nals: as, H. 1: 24; Ann. 1: 18, 56, 80. This is usually preceded by adeo, tantus, tam, more rarely by is or eo, and once by ita (Agr. 18). This use of the tense in Cicero and Caesar is very rare, is wholly wanting in Sallust, somewhat used by Livy, and very frequently by Suetonius and Nepos.

Quin instead of quo minus (Ann. 14: 29) : quin ultra bellum prope- ret, morte prohibitus est.

Quo minus also is sometimes adversative in meaning: as, Agr. 203 Ann. 1: 21, nihil reliqui faciunt quo minus invidiam—permoverent; also 5: 5, 13: 14, 14: 39. In the History, quo minus is found instead of quin or the infin.

Tacitus uses both these particles more extensively than other writers.
